      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same existence, regardless of the distance separating them.  If you measure a property of one entangled particle, like its spin, you instantly know the corresponding property of the other, even if it's across the galaxy.  This is fundamentally different from classical correlation, like knowing two gloves are a pair before you look at them; in entanglement, the properties aren't fixed until the moment of measurement. It's like the particles are communicating faster than light, though no actual information is being transmitted in a classical sense.",
      "source": "target",
