    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i keep seeing people call it \"spooky action at a distance.\" why did einstein call it that? is there something actually weird or unexplainable about how they stay connected?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because he found the instantaneous connection between entangled particles so counterintuitive to his classical understanding of physics. He felt it implied some kind of unphysical, faster-than-light influence was happening between the particles. The weirdness lies in the fact that the particles don't possess definite properties *before* the measurement; the act of measuring one instantly \"collapses\" the shared quantum state for both. It's not that they are secretly sending a signal, but rather that they are described by a single, unified quantum state.",
      "source": "target",
